8/5/21, 00:54 - William R. Ebenezer: Suno. As you start driving faster (at normal speeds) remember these things.. 

1. If there's a sudden obstacle on the road immediately in front, never try to steer away from it. That could lead to toppling. Apply brakes instead and maintain trajectory.

2. Wear seatbelts at all times when in the front seat! Even if the car is stationary, it is good practice to keep them on. 

3. Don't oversteer when at high speeds (40+). There could be toppling or loss of traction. And always remember to drive based on the weather and condition of the road.

4. Safety first, always!

9/15/21, 19:31 - William R. Ebenezer: Dear Students,

This is to inform you that I have removed Nilesh Sureshbhai Das from the position of your Class Representative with immediate effect.

He has sent an audacious email on behalf of the whole class declaring the boycott of all classes starting tomorrow, to the Departmental Head and to all faculty, without any prior consultation with any of the two faculty advisors. Our Head has forwarded his email to the Dean, who will take appropriate steps.

Henceforth, Nilesh Sureshbhai Das is barred from sending any email on behalf of the whole class either to me or any other faculty. If he does so, further disciplinary action shall be initiated against him.

I would remind all the students that you have come to IIT Kharagpur through years of hard work, to build your career for a better future for yourself and your family, in this highly competitive world. You have not come to IIT to join some revolutionary party that dreams of transforming the society or the contemporary education system. Please do not give in to any insinuation from any of your classmates or colleagues, which might hurt your academic career in the future.

There are many more polite, civilized ways of making a statement than threatening the authorities with a boycott, which is a purely political weapon. IIT Kharagpur is one of the top 5 academic institutes of the country, and not a political institution. The language of discourse here must be one of logic and persuasion rather than that of boycott and subversion.

Hope you find sense in my email and refrain from any boycott of classes. The state of West Bengal (where IIT Kharagpur is located, in case you didn't know) has not yet allowed any in-person classes in any of the schools, colleges and universities in the state. I even reminded you in our last online meeting that both law and order and health are state subjects, and the state's official nod is required. 

I can understand and empathize with your impatience, but you must be respectful to the constitution of our federal democracy that allows each state to decide its own rules and regulations in most matters (including health, and law and order). What is happening in Delhi or Punjab is neither automatically applicable to nor can be imposed on West Bengal by any stretch of imagination!

Thanks for your attention.
Best,  
Dr. Saikat Chakraborty

9/16/21, 09:55 - William R. Ebenezer: You know that fluid speeds up when passed through a converging nozzle na?
9/16/21, 09:56 - William R. Ebenezer: And slows down when passed through a diverging one
9/16/21, 09:56 - William R. Ebenezer: Turns out, this is reversed in Mach numbers > 1
9/16/21, 09:57 - William R. Ebenezer: So what the CD nozzle does is, a high subsonic flow speeds up initially till the throat.. and we make it such that the backpressure and initial conditions are such that the flow gets accelerated to M=1 at the throat
9/16/21, 09:57 - William R. Ebenezer: And then, it actually continues to speed up past the throat!
9/16/21, 09:58 - William R. Ebenezer: This also would help you appreciate that you can never accelerate a flow beyond M=1 for a converging nozzle
